{"questionId":"14475","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A random variable <em>Z</em> is normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation 1. It is known&nbsp;that P(<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"z\">\n  <mi>z</mi>\n</math></span> &lt; −1.6) = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span> and P(<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"z\">\n  <mi>z</mi>\n</math></span> &gt; 2.4) = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"b\">\n  <mi>b</mi>\n</math></span>. This is shown in the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/4dac3e8537896149e0c308ce72d6b169aaf5fe6b.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A second random variable <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"X\">\n  <mi>X</mi>\n</math></span> is normally distributed with mean <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"m\">\n  <mi>m</mi>\n</math></span> and standard deviation <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"s\">\n  <mi>s</mi>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p>It is known that P(<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> &lt; 1) = <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"a\">\n  <mi>a</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down the standardized value for&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x = 1\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>1</mn>\n</math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"z = - 1.6\">\n  <mi>z</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>1.6</mn>\n</math></span> (may be seen in part (d))&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1&nbsp; N1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Depending on the candidate’s interpretation of the question, they may give&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{1 - m}}{s}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mi>m</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mi>s</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> as the answer to part (c). Such answers should be awarded the first <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> in part (d), even when part (d) is left blank. If the candidate goes on to show <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"z&nbsp;= - 1.6\">\n  <mi>z</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>1.6</mn>\n</math></span> as part of their working in part (d), the <em><strong>A1</strong> </em>in part (c) may be awarded.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14475","referenceCode":"19M.1.SL.TZ1.S_9c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Write down the standardized value for x = 1 .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.6—Combined, mutually exclusive, conditional, independence, prob diagrams","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.9—Normal distribution and calculations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}